  "summary": "**FACTUAL SUMMARY:**  \nAcross the 64 timesteps the market narrative has been dominated by alternating spikes in oil prices driven by geopolitical shocks (Ukraine\u2011Russia tensions, U.S.\u2011China and U.S.\u2011India tariff threats, and occasional OPEC\u207a output hikes) and sharp pull\u2011backs whenever inventory builds, sanctions, or aggressive OPEC\u207a supply expansions were announced.  Equity markets have repeatedly rallied on expectations of Federal Reserve rate cuts\u2014most often priced for an October\u2011December easing cycle\u2014while tech\u2011heavy indices have shown volatility around AI earnings and tariff\u2011related risk\u2011off moves.  Energy\u2011sector fundamentals have been strained by low U.S. rig counts, persistent oversupply, and a wave of workforce reductions at majors, yet occasional price spikes (e.g., when Brent breached $70\u202f/\u202fbbl) have kept oil\u2011linked stocks intermittently buoyant.\n\n**PREDICTIVE SIGNALS:**  \nAnalysts expect the near\u2011term oil price trajectory to hinge on three catalysts: (1) the outcome of the August\u202f1\u2011August\u202f30 U.S. tariff deadline and any secondary duties on Indian or Russian oil, which could push Brent back toward the $70\u202f/\u202fbbl zone if enforced; (2) the Fed\u2019s likely October rate cut (\u224890\u202f% probability) followed by a possible December cut, which should support risk assets and modestly lift demand\u2011sensitive crude; and (3) OPEC\u207a\u2019s scheduled production increase in September\u2011October, which, if fully implemented, will sustain oversupply pressure and keep WTI near $60\u2011$63\u202f/\u202fbbl unless offset by a sudden supply shock (e.g., renewed Ukraine\u2011Russia pipeline attacks).  Consequently, the consensus view is for a relatively flat\u2011to\u2011slightly\u2011lower oil price outlook through Q4\u202f2025, with upside potential only if tariff escalations or geopolitical disruptions materialize.",
